<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 413px; float: right;">Let's go straight to the meat: we just shipped&nbsp;<a href="https://maven.apache.org/" target="_blank">Maven</a>&nbsp;support! If you're packaging <span style="font-style: italic;">.jar</span>&nbsp;and <span style="font-style: italic;">.war</span>&nbsp;(or Android <span style="font-style: italic;">.aar</span>) and have a <span style="font-style: italic;">pom.xml</span>&nbsp;to go with them, you can now add these to your MyGet feeds (or should we start calling them repositories).</p><p>Maven support is enabled on all MyGet accounts - starting today, you access to the Maven features <a href="https://docs.myget.org/docs/walkthrough/getting-started-with-maven" target="_blank">described in our documentation</a>.</p><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 24px;">Which features are available?</span></p><p>We currently support almost all features we have available for other package managers: uploading your own packages (via the web UI as well as via <code>mvn</code> or Gradle) and adding packages from upstream repositories like Maven Central. Packages can then be consumed in IntelliJ IDEA or Eclipse, using Maven or Gradle. It's possible to proxy upstream repositories into your MyGet feed. You can manage permissions and users, inspect package licenses and vulnerabilities, ...</p><p>A Maven repository on MyGet can also be used as a staging area: packages and snapshots can be published on MyGet, and once they are stable, pushed upstream to another repository out there - similar to what is possible for NuGet and NPM.</p><p>We're looking into supporting build services as well (theoretically you can already create a build.bat and invoke `mvn deploy` from it), but we'd love your feedback on what the perfect convention-based build for Maven/Gradle would look like.</p><h3>Awesome! How do I get started?</h3><p>Quite easy: head over to <a href="http://www.myget.org" target="_blank">www.myget.org</a>, sign in (or register) and create a feed. Our <a href="https://docs.myget.org/docs/walkthrough/getting-started-with-maven" target="_blank">getting started documentation</a>&nbsp;has some more details on how to upload your first Maven package to MyGet.</p><p>We're really excited about introducing Maven support on MyGet! You can now use MyGet to securely host and collaborate on NuGet, symbols and sources, Chocolatey, PowerShell, NPM, Bower, Maven and VSIX packages.</p><p><span style="font-style: italic;">Happy packaging!</span></p>
